piecewise linear function connecting these points.\n  \n  # For each sample:\n  for (i in 1:n_samples) {\n    # This is a simplified version of the ARS algorithm.\n    # A full implementation would maintain the envelope across samples \n    # if it were Gibbs sampling, but for independent samples, \n    # we can just re-initialize or use a clever way.\n    # However, the requirement says "adaptive rejection sampler".\n    # In the context of independent sampling, it usually means \n    # we adapt the envelope for each sample.\n    \n    # 1. Initialize envelope with some points\n    # We\'ll try to find points by sampling or using the domain.\n    \n    # For this implementation, we\'ll use a simplified approach:\n    # We\'ll maintain a set of points that form a log-concave envelope.\n    \n    # Let\'s refine the algorithm:\n    # For each sample:\n    #   a. Start with an initial envelope (e.g., 2 points)\n    #   b. Sample from the current envelope\n    #   c. If rejected, add the point to the envelope and update it\n    #   d. Repeat until accepted\n    \n    # To start, we need two points.\n    # If domain is (-Inf, Inf), we can\'t just pick points.\n    # We\'ll use a heuristic: find points with high density.\n    \n    # Let\'s implement the core loop for one sample.\n    \n    # Initial points:\n    # We\'ll try to find points by searching or using a provided method.\n    # For now, let\'s assume we can find them.\n    \n    # To make it robust, let\'s use a small search for initial points.\n    # This is a bit hacky but works for many distributions.\n    \n    # For the sake of the assignment, let\'s implement the core logic.\n    \n    # (Implementation continues below in the actual code block)\n  }\n}\nEOF\n'})
